t enable analysts to provide the most informed assessment possible regarding an army's likely response to a revolution and, ultimately, the probable fate of the revolution itself. He examines such factors as the military's internal cohesion, the regime's treatment of its armed forces, and the size, composition, and nature of the demonstrations.How Armies Respond to Revolutions and Why explains how generals decide to support or suppress domestic uprisings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aComparative government. 0aMilitary policyxDecision makingvCase studies. 0aRevolutionsxHistoryy21st centuryvCase studies. 0aWorld politicsy1989-. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aArab republics.  aArab-majority states.  aAyatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.  aBurma.  aChina.  aCommunism.  aEastern Europe.  aFour Eight Uprising.  aIAF.  aImperial Armed Forces.  aIran.  aIranian military.  aIslamic Revolution.  aMiddle East.  aMohammad Reza Shah Pahlavi.  aNe Win.  aNorth Africa.  aPeople Power Uprising.  aRomania.  aSaffron Revolution.  aWarsaw Pact.  aarmed forces.  aarmy response.  acivil-military relations.  acivilЭilitary relations.  aconscript army.  acontrolling unrest.  ademocratization.  adomestic revolt.  adomestic uprising.  aempirical analysis.  aexplanatory factors.  aexternal environment.  aforeign intervention.  amilitary cohesion.  amilitary decision-making.  amilitary establishment.  amilitary regimes.  amilitary response.  amilitary.  apolitical dynamics.  apolitical upheavals.  apopular uprisings.  aprotests.  aregime change.  aregime coercion.  aregime legitimacy.  aregular army.  arevolution.  arevolutions.  asociety.  astate.  avolunteer army.08iTitle is part of eBook pa